Provenance of this page
Ontology Specification Draft

Abstract

The EPD+ILCD Dataset Ontology presents a knowledge model that formalizes the semantic representation of Environmental Product Declarations (EPDs) and Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) data for building materials and products according to the EPD+ILCD format. This ontology provides a structured framework for capturing comprehensive environmental impact data, administrative information, and process-related metadata, while enabling hierarchical classification of construction materials and their associated environmental indicators. Developed under Creative Commons licensing, it facilitates semantic interoperability and standardized data exchange within the construction sector's environmental assessment domain.

Introduction back to ToC

Background and Motivation The construction industry's growing focus on sustainability and environmental impact has led to an increased need for standardized ways to represent and share environmental performance data. Environmental Product Declarations (EPDs) have become crucial documents for communicating the environmental impacts of building materials and products throughout their lifecycle. However, the complex nature of EPD data, combined with varying formats and standards across different organizations and regions, creates significant challenges for data integration, comparison, and analysis. The EPD+ILCD Dataset Ontology addresses these challenges by providing a formal semantic framework that combines the comprehensive environmental assessment approach of EPDs with the structured data format of the International Life Cycle Data (ILCD) system. This integration enables standardized representation of environmental impact data while maintaining the detailed hierarchical classification needed for construction materials and products. State of the Art Current approaches to EPD data management often rely on disparate data formats and structures, leading to challenges in data exchange and integration. While standards such as EN 15804 and ISO 14025 provide guidelines for EPD content, there remains a need for semantic frameworks that can facilitate automated data processing and integration across different systems. The EPD+ILCD Dataset Ontology builds upon existing standards and extends them with a comprehensive semantic model that captures: Detailed environmental impact indicators and their life cycle phases Administrative and validation information Process data set relationships and classifications Quantitative references and units of measurement Ontology Structure and Components The ontology is organized around several key components: Core Classes: ProcessDataSet: Represents the main container for EPD information EnvironmentalIndicator: Captures environmental impact measurements AdministrativeInformation: Manages metadata and ownership details ClassificationOrCategory: Provides hierarchical classification of materials Environmental Indicators: Core environmental impact indicators (e.g., GWP, ODP, AP) Resource use indicators Waste category indicators Additional environmental impact indicators Life Cycle Information: Comprehensive coverage of life cycle phases (A1-D) Modelling and validation information Scenario and module definitions Data Management: Validation and compliance declarations Time and technological representativeness Data quality and documentation Goals and Objectives The primary objectives of the EPD+ILCD Dataset Ontology include: Standardization: Provide a formal semantic framework for representing EPD and LCA data in a standardized format. Interoperability: Enable seamless data exchange between different stakeholders and systems in the construction industry. Data Quality: Support comprehensive documentation of data quality, validation, and compliance information. Classification: Establish a flexible and extensible classification system for building materials and their environmental characteristics. Life Cycle Assessment: Support detailed representation of life cycle phases and their associated environmental impacts. Applications and Significance The ontology serves various stakeholders in the construction industry: Manufacturers: Standardized representation of product environmental declarations Designers and Engineers: Easy access to comparable environmental impact data Researchers: Structured framework for analyzing environmental performance Software Developers: Clear schema for developing EPD-related applications Certification Bodies: Support for validation and compliance checking Current Development and Future Directions Currently at version 0.1, the ontology provides a foundation for EPD data representation while maintaining flexibility for future extensions. Future developments may include: Integration with other construction-domain ontologies Extension of environmental impact indicators Enhancement of data quality assessment frameworks Development of alignment with emerging sustainability standards Ensure to study the structure and use the sparql queries as a guide to understand the structure. The ontology's open license (Creative Commons 4.0) encourages community involvement and adaptation, ensuring its evolution alongside industry needs and technological advances. >

EPD+ILCD Dataset Ontology: Description back to ToC

An ontology for representing Environmental Product Declaration Life Cycle Assessment data sets according to the EPD+ILCD format.

Additional Environmental Impact Indicatorsc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/AdditionalEnvironmentalImpactIndicators

Supplementary environmental impact indicators beyond the core mandatory impact categories
This class encompasses additional environmental impact indicators that extend beyond the core mandatory impact categories required by EPD standards. These may include specialized impact categories such as human toxicity potential, ecotoxicity potential, ionizing radiation potential, land use impacts, fossil resource scarcity, and other emerging impact categories. These additional indicators provide a more comprehensive environmental assessment and may be required by specific EPD programs or building certification schemes.

Input Indicators Describing Resource Usec back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/InputIndicatorsDescribingResourceUse

Indicators that quantify the consumption of various resources during the life cycle
This class represents indicators that describe the input flows related to resource consumption throughout the life cycle of a building product or material. These indicators include the use of renewable and non-renewable primary energy, secondary materials, secondary fuels, and fresh water resources. These inputs are fundamental for understanding the resource depletion impacts and efficiency of building materials and products in accordance with the EPD+ILCD methodology.

Indicators of Life Cycle c
is in domain of

This class represents indicators that describe the output flows related to waste generation and disposal throughout the life cycle of a building product or material. These indicators include quantities of hazardous waste disposed, non-hazardous waste disposed, radioactive waste disposed, materials for recycling, materials for energy recovery, and components for re-use. These outputs are essential for understanding the end-of-life environmental implications and circular economy potential of building materials.
has super-classes
Indicators of Life Cycle c
is in domain of
is output indicators describing waste categories of op
is in range of
has Output Indicators Describing Waste Categories op
has members
Components for reuse (CRU) ni, Exported electrical energy (EEE) ni, Exported thermal energy (EET) ni, Hazardous waste disposed (HWD) ni, Materials for energy recovery (MER) ni, Materials for recycling (MFR) ni, Non hazardous waste dispose (NHWD) ni, Radioactive waste disposed (RWD) ni

has Additional Environmental Impact Indicatorsop back to ToC or Object Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/hasAdditionalEnvironmentalImpactIndicators

Associates core environmental impact indicators with additional supplementary impact indicators
This property connects EnvironmentalImpactIndicators to AdditionalEnvironmentalImpactIndicators, which represent supplementary environmental impact categories beyond the core mandatory indicators. These may include toxicity indicators, land use impacts, ionizing radiation, and other specialized impact categories that provide a more comprehensive environmental assessment.

has characteristics: functional

has domain
Environmental Impact Indicators c
has range
Additional Environmental Impact Indicators c
is inverse of
is additional environmental impact indicators of op

This property connects an EnvironmentalIndicator to its IndicatorsOfLifeCycle component, which encompasses both input indicators describing resource use and output indicators describing waste categories. This relationship is essential for organizing life cycle assessment data according to the EPD+ILCD format.

Biogenic Carbon Contentdp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/BiogenicCarbonContent

Specifies the biogenic carbon content of the reference flow
This property provides information about the biogenic carbon content in the quantitative reference flow of the product. Biogenic carbon refers to carbon derived from renewable biological sources, which plays an important role in carbon footprint calculations and climate change impact assessments. The value is typically expressed as a percentage or absolute amount of biogenic carbon present in the declared unit.
has domain
Quantitative Reference c
has range
string

Content Declarationdp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/ContentDeclaration

Data Set Versiondp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/DataSetVersion

The version of the data set
Version number of data set; is automatically generated. First two digits refer to major updates, the second two digits to minor revisions and error corrections etc. The last three digits are intended for automatic and internal counting of versions during data set development. Together with the data set's UUID, the "Data set version" uniquely identifies each data set. Find further explanations in FAQ.
has domain
Publication and Ownership c
has range
string

Subtypedp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/Subtype

The subtype of the modelling and validation
Indicates the type of data set regarding its representativeness. One of the following predefined data types has to be chosen: - specific dataset - vendor (company) specific data for a specific product from one production site - average dataset - average datasets from industry associations, multiple manufacturers, multiple poduction sites or multiple products, i.e. modelled based on industry data from a manufacturer - representative dataset - data that is representative for a country or region (e.g. average for Germany) - template dataset - sample EPD, unspecific datasets for specific products, that were created based on a sample EPD - generic dataset - generic data acc. to EN 15804 and data based on other non- industry data sources (e.g. literature, expert knowledge)
has domain
Modelling and Validation c
has range
string

Technical Purpose of Product or Processdp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/TechnicalPurposeOfProductOrProcess

The technical purpose of the product or process
Brief description of the intended use / possible applications of the good, service, or process, e.g. for which type of products the material, represented by this data set, is used. For construction products the feasible applications in the building shall be given. Note: This corresponds to EN 15804, section 7.1 b) 'description of the construction product's use […]'. Find further explanations and examples in FAQ.
has domain
Technological Representativeness c
has range
string

Technology Description Including Background Systemdp back to ToC or Data Property ToC

IRI: http://www.EpdLcaOntology.com/EpdLcaDataSetOntology/TechnologyDescriptionIncludingBackgroundSystem

Description of the technology including the background system
Description of the technological characteristics including operating conditions of the product system or process. If relevant for the technological representativeness this comprises the technological characteristics of the relevant upstream and downstream processes ("background system") included in the data set. Link to detailed description in EPD-document or to flow diagramm can be given, if available. Note 1: The feasible application of the product in the building or of the material in a process or product respectively is described in the field 'technical purpose of product or process' (8); a reference to the corresponding section of the EPD can be given. Note 2: No general descriptions of the system boundaries according to EN 15804. Find further explanations and examples in FAQ.
has domain
Technological Representativeness c
has range
string

Abiotic Depletion Potential - Fossil Resources (ADPF) measures the potential for a substance to deplete fossil fuel resources. The unit for ADPF is typically "MJ".

Eutrophication potential - freshwater
Eutrophication Potential - Freshwater (EP-Freshwater) assesses the potential of a substance to cause excessive nutrient accumulation in freshwater ecosystems, leading to harmful algal blooms. The unit for EP-Freshwater is typically "kg P-eq" (kilograms of phosphate equivalent).

Eutrophication potential - marine
Eutrophication Potential - Marine (EP-Marine) measures the potential of a substance to cause excessive nutrient buildup in marine ecosystems, which can result in harmful algal blooms. The unit for EP-Marine is typically "kg N eq" (kilograms of nitrogen equivalent).
belongs to
